In article <1994Apr25.225100.20538@news.unomaha.edu> ddoumake@unomaha.edu (DONALD JAMES DOUMAKES) writes:
>Clive D.W. Feather (clive@sco.com) wrote:
>: An organisation I am associated with is going to send a questionnaire to
>: all its members. In order to encourage people to return them, we are
>: going to select one at random and give its sender a small prize
>: (sufficient to motivate them to return it, but not enough to make serious
>: fraud a problem).
>: At the same time, we want the questionnaires to be anonymous and to be
>: seen to be anonymous.
>There's a low-tech and low-stress solution to this.  Use two return
>envelopes, one nested inside the other.

>A trusted individual isn't really necessary to protect the
>respondents' anonymity, since the inner envelopes remain sealed (a fact that
>a referee can verify).

Of course, the referee must also check that the envelopes remain
unmarked as well.

This works if we can find a mutually trusted referee. I would like to
find a system that doesn't need one. We also need to have the digested
results of the questionnaires available for the public meeting at which
the draw will be held.

